“It doesn’t feel pretentious at all,” she said. “It really feels like a community art space.”  

**BROWSING BOOKS, BROWSING ART**
---

Many local libraries across the state have gallery spaces for visual art, with some booking artists more than a year in advance to provide visitors a chance to browse art while they also browse for books. As older buildings are renovated and expanded to accommodate growth and changing needs, many libraries have also invested in formal and informal ways to display art. 

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_5.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_5.jpg)

Circulation manager Virginia Kiesewetter organizes books at the Falmouth Memorial Library. The illustrations above the bookshelves are on display during The Great State of Illustration in Maine exhibit. (Daryn Slover/Staff Photographer)

The Thomas Memorial Library in Cape Elizabeth has shown the work of Maine artists for more than 40 years. Pieces were hung in the walkway between the old building and the annex, and in the most recent library renovation, there’s a dedicated gallery space in the basement. 

“It helps people to see what’s possible and the things they make with their own hands and imaginations,” said Library Director Rachel Davis. “It helps to promote visual literacy. They don’t need to make a special trip to see the artwork.” 

Davis ultimately decides which artists display their work in month-long installments. A creative herself, she likes to hunt through magazine articles and galleries for promising talent, in addition to reading applications. The library’s space is currently booked through August for works by artists who have made a career of it, as well as amateurs looking for a place to show and sell their work.

Other libraries are also catching on. 

