Before Augusta’s Lithgow Public Library expanded in 2016, there were no spaces for rotating art exhibitions. “Every single spot was filled,” said Director Sarah Schultz-Nielsen. The one meeting room in the basement of the original building, which was built in 1896, was primarily used for filling interlibrary loan requests. 

The expansion nearly tripled the size of the library, creating new community gathering areas and new opportunities to share art. 

The teen room has displayed mixed media work by students from the Maine Arts Academy about banned books since November, the space’s first exhibit. 

The community meeting room will have [its first exhibit in February](https://www.lithgowlibrary.org/) of flowers captured by photographers affiliated with the Brunswick’s First Light Camera Club. Two participating photographers – Allen Cairns and Ella Hudson – will give a talk on Feb. 3, teaching guests how to take high-quality photos with their phones. 

Schultz-Nielsen said Augusta doesn’t have as many gallery spaces as neighboring towns like Gardiner or Hallowell. She hopes the library can fill that void. 

“We’re a natural place to be able to offer it,” she said.  

