And libraries are broadening what exhibitions look like, incorporating them into their programming. 

All of the available wall space at Falmouth Memorial Library – including the area near the circulation desk that has been showing art since its renovation in 2019 – is devoted to [The Great State of Illustration in Maine](https://www.falmouthmemoriallibrary.org/art-at-the-library-2/), an exhibit put on in partnership with the Illustration Institute, a Portland nonprofit supporting illustrators and illustration education. 

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_6.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_6.jpg)

Illustrations are on display throughout the Falmouth Memorial Library during The Great State of Illustration in Maine exhibit. (Daryn Slover/Staff Photographer)

In the exhibit, a baseball player swings above the new fiction releases. A cartoon lobster fly-fishes above a cushioned armchair. A pastel print of Mt. Katahdin hangs near the DVDs. 

“There’s a whole flow to it,” said Library Director Jenna Mayotte. “When it’s using the whole space, it’s giving it a fresh look and exposing people to new things.”

The exhibit has helped draw more traffic to the library, too, she said. 

The library fundraised $20,000 to put up the exhibit, and took down almost all of its permanent art collection to show these 90 illustrations made by artists with ties to Maine, its first professionally curated exhibit. 

