The traveling exhibit has been shown in the Brick Store Museum in Kennebunk, the Ticonic Gallery in Waterville and a University of Maine Augusta gallery in the last four years. This is its first library. 

“It’s quite different from just putting up artwork on bare gallery walls,” said Will Roth, an assistant curator with the Illustration Institute.

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_4.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2026/01/43351757_20260109_Library-Art-Falmouth_4.jpg)

Kelly Shinnick, left, and Darcy Cochroan, both of Portland, work together under an illustration by Isabella Rotman at the Falmouth Memorial Library. (Daryn Slover/Staff Photographer)

The bookshelves could be obstacles to viewing the art, he said, so they included wayfinding elements – like a vinyl banner at the start of the exhibit – to help visitors navigate the space.

Individual pieces were intentionally placed. The quiet reading room at the end of the building, for example, featured pen and ink drawings and cartoons, which Roth described as “subdued, delicate and intricate works.”

“They sort of reflect the contemplative mood of the space,” he said. 

The Illustration Institute has helped the library provide programming directly related to the exhibit, including a sneaker painting workshop led by Eamon White, one of the artists whose work is featured in the show. Scott Nash, one of the founders of the Illustration Institute, will host a “draw-off” on Jan. 31, the last day of the exhibit, where visitors get to make art themselves.

