“It brings our walls to life,” Mayotte said.

**ART** THAT’S ACCESSIBLE
---

Local artists have embraced libraries as accessible gallery spaces. There are rarely any submission fees.

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/43351757_20260112_Library003.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2026/01/43351757_20260112_Library003.jpg)

“Narrative” by Kharris Brill, on display in the Stier Family Gallery at the Thomas Memorial Library in Cape Elizabeth. (Shawn Patrick Ouellette/Staff Photographer)

Kathryn Brill, who [makes art under the name Kharris B](https://www.pressherald.com/2024/04/15/coyote-teeth-moss-clock-gears-find-it-all-in-this-bath-artists-studio/), has shown her work in libraries across Maine, including in Portland and Tenants Harbor. A collection of her pieces are on display in the Stier Family Gallery in the Thomas Memorial Library through the end of January.

She makes assemblages out of “strange material, unexpected stuff” like motorcycle carburetors. Old cameras and their lenses. Gears. Typewriter pieces. 

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2026/01/38371471_20240409_AssemblageArtist_10.jpg?w=250&h=250&crop=1)](https://www.pressherald.com/2024/04/15/coyote-teeth-moss-clock-gears-find-it-all-in-this-bath-artists-studio/)

